Arthur Mizener author of the acclaimed first 
biography of F Scott Fitzgerald has died at the age of 80 
Mizener died of congestive heart failure Thursday at the 
Bristol RI nursing home where he had lived 
The Far Side of Paradise Mizeners bestselling biography 
of Fitzgerald was published in 1951 by Houghton Mifflin a decade 
after a heart attack ended the downward spiraling career of the 
chronicler of the Jazz Age of the 1920s 
The biography was credited with reviving interest in Fitzgerald 
now considered one of the great American novelists of the 20th 
Century 
Fitzgerald wrote This Side of Paradise The Great 
Gatsby Tender Is the Night and The Last Tycoon as well 
as numerous short stories 
Mizener taught English at Cornell University from 1951 until his 
retirement in 1975 He wrote scores of essays and book reviews for 
many publications 
Born in Erie Pa he graduated from Princeton University in 
1930 received his masters degree from Harvard University in 1932 
and returned to Princeton where he received his doctorate in 1934 
A memorial service is to be held at noon on Feb 27 at the 
United Congregational Church in Little Compton 
He is survived by a daughter Rosemary Colt of Little Compton 
RI a sister Virginia Jarecki of Erie and three grandchildren 
